# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: smart-farming-iot
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture includes (but is not limited to) precision agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Unlike precision agriculture, digital agriculture impacts the entire agri-food value chain before, during, and after on-farm production.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Therefore, on-farm technologies like yield mapping, GPS navigation, and tracking, and variable-rate application, fall under the domain of precision agriculture *and* digital agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] On the other hand, digital technologies involved in e-commerce platforms, e-extension services, warehouse receipt systems, blockchain-enabled food traceability systems, tractor rental apps, etc. fall under the umbrella of digital agriculture but not precision agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital technologies are changing traditional agricultural practices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Precise dates of the Fourth Agricultural Revolution are unclear.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] The World Economic Forum announced that the "Fourth Industrial Revolution" (which includes agriculture) will unfold throughout the 21st century, so the beginning of Agriculture 4.0 is often placed around 2000 or shortly thereafter.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Agricultural revolutions denote periods of technological transformation and increased farm productivity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Agricultural revolutions include the First Agricultural Revolution, the Arab Agricultural Revolution, the British/Second Agricultural Revolution, the Scottish Agricultural Revolution, and the Green Revolution/Third Agricultural Revolution.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Despite boosting agricultural productivity, past agricultural revolutions left many problems unsolved.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] For example, the Green Revolution had unintended consequences, like inequality and environmental damage.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] First, the Green Revolution exacerbated inter-farm and interregional inequality, typically biased toward large farmers with the capital to invest in new technologies.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Second, critics say its policies promoted heavy input use and dependence on agrochemicals, which led to adverse environmental effects like soil degradation and chemical runoff.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture technologies have the potential to address negative side effects of the Green Revolution.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In some ways, the Digital Agriculture Revolution follows patterns of previous agricultural revolutions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Scholars forecast a further shift away from labor, a slight shift away from capital, and intensified use of human capital, continuing the trend the British Agricultural Revolution started.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Also, many predict that social backlash, possibly around the use of artificial intelligence or robots, will arise with the fourth revolution.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In other ways, the Digital Agriculture Revolution is distinct from its predecessors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] First, digital technologies will affect *all* parts of the agricultural value chain, including off-farm segments.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] This differs from the first three agricultural revolutions, which primarily impacted production techniques and on-farm technologies.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Second, a farmer's role will require more data analytics skills and less physical interaction with livestock/fields.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Third, although farming has always relied on empirical evidence, the volume of data and the methods of analysis will undergo drastic changes in the digital revolution.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] For example, smart farm systems continuously monitor animal behavior, giving insight into their activities at all times.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Finally, increased reliance on big data may increase the power differential between farmers and information service providers, or between farmers and large value chain actors (like supermarkets).
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture encompasses a wide range of technologies, most of which have multiple applications along the agricultural value chain.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] The FAO estimates the world will need to produce 56% more food (as compared to 2010, under "business as usual" growth) to feed over 9 billion in 2050.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Furthermore, the world faces intersecting challenges like malnutrition, climate change, food waste, and changing diets.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] To produce a "sustainable food future," the world must increase food production while cutting greenhouse gas emissions and maintaining (or reducing) the land used in agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture can potentially address these challenges by making the agricultural value chain more efficient, equitable, and environmentally sustainable.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital technology changes economic activity by lowering the costs of replicating, transporting, tracking, verifying, and searching for data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Due to these falling costs, digital technology can improve efficiency throughout the agricultural value chain.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] On-farm, precision agriculture technologies can minimize inputs required for a given yield.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] For example, variable-rate application (VRA) technologies can apply precise amounts of water, fertilizer, pesticide, herbicide, etc.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] A number of empirical studies find that VRA improves input use efficiency.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Using VRA alongside geo-spatial mapping, farmers can apply inputs to hyper-localized regions of their farm, sometimes down to the individual plant level.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Reducing input use lowers costs and lessens negative environmental impacts.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Furthermore, empirical evidence indicates precision agriculture technologies can increase yields.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] On U.S. peanut farms, guidance systems are associated with a 9% increase in yield, and soil maps are associated with a 13% increase in yield.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] One study in Argentina found that a precision agriculture approach based on crop physiological principles could result in 54% higher farm output.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture can improve the allocative efficiency of physical capital within and between farms.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Often touted as "Uber for tractors," equipment-sharing platforms like Hello Tractor, WeFarmUp, MachineryLink Solutions, TroTro Tractor, and Tringo facilitate farmer rental of expensive machinery, an on-demand model with parallels to Public transport.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] These platforms are an example of agricultural Fleet management, often coordinated with Fleet management software.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] By facilitating a market for equipment sharing, telematics technology ensures fewer tractors sit idle and allows owners to make extra income.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture improves labor productivity through improved farmer knowledge.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] E-extension (electronic provision of traditional agricultural extension services) allows for farming knowledge and skills to diffuse at low cost.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] For example, the company Digital Green works with local farmers to create and disseminate videos about agricultural best practices in more than 50 languages.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] E-extension services can also improve farm productivity via decision-support services on mobile apps or other digital platforms.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Using many sources of information, such as weather data, GIS spatial mapping, soil sensor data, and satellite/drone pictures, e-extension platforms can provide real-time recommendations to farmers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] For example, the machine-learning-enabled mobile app Plantix, Krisikart India diagnoses crops' diseases, pests, and nutrient deficiencies based on a smartphone photo.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In a randomized control trial, Casaburi et al.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] (2014) found that sugarcane growers who received agricultural advice via SMS messages increased yields by 11.5% relative to the control group.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Finally, digital agriculture improves labor productivity through decreased labor requirements.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Automation inherent in precision agriculture, from "milking robots on dairy farms to greenhouses with automated climate control," can make crop and livestock management more efficient by reducing required labor.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Besides streamlining farm production, digital agriculture technologies can make agricultural markets more efficient.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Mobile phones, online ICTs, e-commerce platforms, digital payment systems, and other digital agriculture technologies can mitigate market failures and reduce transaction costs throughout the value chain.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Typically, a system of digital agriculture technologies, rather than a single tool, is used to solve multifaceted problems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] For example, e-commerce solves two efficiency issues: difficulty matching buyers and sellers, especially in rural areas, and the high transaction costs associated with in-person, cash-based trade.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture shows promise for creating a more equitable agri-food value chain.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture technologies can expand farmers' access to credit, insurance, and bank accounts for a number of reasons.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] First, digital technology helps alleviate the information asymmetry that exists between farmers and financial institutions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] When lenders decide a farmer's credit ceiling or insurance premium, they are usually uncertain about what risks the farmer presents.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital technology reduces the costs of verifying farmers' expected riskiness.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] The Kenyan company M-Shwari uses customers' phone and mobile money records to assess creditworthiness.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Organizations like FarmDrive and Apollo Agriculture incorporate satellite imagery, weather forecasts, and remote sensor data when calculating farmers' loan eligibility.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Drone imagery can confirm a farmer's physical assets or land use and Asset tracking using RFID technology allows stakeholders to monitor livestock, making it easier for insurers to understand farmers' riskiness.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In all instances, low-cost digital verification reduces lenders' uncertainty: the questions "will this farmer repay the loan?" and "what risks does this farmer face?" become clearer.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Second, digital technology facilitates trust between farmers and financial institutions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] A range of tools create trust, including real-time digital communication platforms and blockchain/distributed ledger technology/smart contracts.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In Senegal, a digitalized, supply-chain-tracking system allows farmers to collateralize their rice to obtain the credit necessary for planting.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Lenders accept rice as collateral because real-time, digital tracking assures them the product was not lost or damaged in the post-harvest process.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Middlemen often extract exorbitant rents from farmers when purchasing their harvest or livestock for several reasons.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] First, smallholders in remote areas may be unaware of fair market prices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] As a result, middlemen (who typically have better information about market conditions and prices) accrue significant market power and profits.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] A study conducted in the central highlands of Peru found that farmers who received market price information via mobile phone SMS increased their sales prices by 13-14% relative to farmers without access to the information.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Second, smallholders produce tiny harvests compared to large producers, so they lack bargaining power with middlemen.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] If smallholders can aggregate or form a cooperative to sell their products together, they have more leverage.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Online platforms and mobile phones can facilitate aggregation, such as Digital Green's Loop app.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Third, connecting producers with final consumers can eliminate intermediaries' monopsony power, thereby raising producer profits.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] As mentioned above in the efficiency section, e-commerce or other market linkage platforms can connect a small farmer directly to consumers around the world.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] While digital technologies can facilitate market access and information flow, their benefits may not be evenly distributed, potentially exacerbating existing inequalities.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Constraints on adoption can result in benefits accruing primarily to more powerful actors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Boosting natural resource efficiency is the "single most important need for a sustainable food future," according to the World Resource Institute.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] As mentioned in the on-farm efficiency section, precision farming, including variable rate nutrient application, variable rate irrigation, machine guidance, and variable rate planting/seeding, could minimize use of agricultural inputs for a given yield.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] This could mitigate resource waste and negative environmental externalities, like greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, soil erosion, and fertilizer runoff.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] 2014 estimate that switching to precision weed management could save up to 30,000 tons of pesticide in the EU-25 countries.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] 2013 found that precision irrigation of a citrus orchard could reduce water use by 25 percent while maintaining a constant yield.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] 2012 demonstrated that variable-rate application of fertilizer can reduce nitrogen application and leaching without affecting yield and net return.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] However, precision agriculture could also accelerate farms' depletion of natural resources because of a rebound effect; increasing input efficiency does not necessarily lead to resource conservation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Off-farm, digital agriculture has the potential to improve environmental monitoring and food system traceability.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] The monitoring costs of certifying compliance with environmental, health, or waste standards are falling because of digital technology.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] For example, satellite and drone imagery can track land use and/or forest cover; distributed ledger technologies can enable trusted transactions and exchange of data; food sensors can monitor temperatures to minimize contamination during storage and transport.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Together, technologies like these can form digital agriculture traceability systems, which allow stakeholders to track agri-food products in near-real-time.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] According to the McKinsey Industry Digitization Index, the agricultural sector is the slowest adopter of digital technologies in the United States.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Farm-level adoption of digital agriculture varies within and between countries, and uptake differs by technology.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Some characterize precision agriculture uptake as rather slow.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In the United States in 2010-2012, precision agriculture technologies were used on 30-50% of corn and soybean acreage.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Others point out that uptake varies by technology; farmer use of GNSS guidance has grown rapidly, but variable-rate technology adoption rarely exceeds 20% of farms.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Furthermore, digital agriculture is not limited to on-farm precision tools, and these innovations typically require less upfront investment.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Growing access to ICTs in agriculture and a booming e-commerce market all bode well for increased adoption of digital agriculture downstream of the farm.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Individual farmers' perceptions about usefulness, ease of use, and cost-effectiveness impact the spread of digital agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Although a few digital technologies can operate in areas with limited mobile phone coverage and internet connectivity, rural network coverage plays an important role in digital agriculture's success.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] A wide gap exists between developed and developing countries' 3G and 4G cellular coverage, and issues such as dropped calls, delays, and weak signals hamper telecommunications efficacy in rural areas.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Even when countries overcome infrastructural challenges, the price of network connectivity can exclude smallholders, poor farmers, and those in remote areas.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Similar accessibility and affordability issues exist for digital devices and digital accounts.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] According to a 2016 GSMA report, of the 750 million-plus farmers in the 69 surveyed countries, about 295 million had a mobile phone; only 13 million had both a mobile phone and a mobile money account.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Despite lingering gaps in network coverage, ICT access has skyrocketed in recent years.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In 2007, only 1% of people in developing countries used Internet, but by 2015, 40% did.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Mobile-broadband subscriptions, which increased thirty-fold between 2005 and 2015, drove much of this growth.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] As a key enabler of agricultural change, digital infrastructure requires further development, but growing ICT access indicates progress.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] The significance and structure of a country's agricultural sector will affect digital agriculture adoption.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] For example, a grain-based economy needs difference technologies than a major vegetable producer.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Automated, digitally-enabled harvesting systems might make sense for grains, pulses and cotton, but only a few specialty crops generate enough value to justify large investments in mechanized or automated harvesting.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Farm size also affects technology choices, as economies of scale make large investments possible (e.g., adoption of precision agriculture is more likely on larger farms).
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] On the other hand, digital agriculture solutions focused on ICTs and e-commerce would benefit an economy dominated by smallholders.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In China, where the average farm size is less than 1 ha, Alibaba's customer-to-customer e-commerce platform called Rural Taobao has helped melon growers in Bachu County market their produce all over the country.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Other structural factors, such as percent of the population employed in agriculture, farm density, farm mechanization rates, and other factors also impact how different regions adopt digital agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In order to benefit from the advent of digital agriculture, farmers must develop new skills.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In many instances, benefiting from digital content also requires English literacy or familiarity with another widely spoken language.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture developers have designed ways around these barriers, such as ICTs with audio messages and extension videos in local languages.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] However, more investment in human capital development is needed to ensure all farmers can benefit from digital agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Fostering human capital in the form of innovation also matters for the spread of digital agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Some characterize digital agriculture innovation, a knowledge- and skills-intensive process, as concentrated in "Big Ag" companies and research universities.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] However, others describe small-scale entrepreneurs as the "heart of the action." In 2018, ag-tech innovation attracted $1.9 billion in venture capital, and the sector has grown significantly in the last 10 years.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Although digital agriculture may be concentrated in a few developed countries because of "structure, institutional, and economic barriers," ag-tech startups have experienced significant growth in Africa, the Caribbean and Pacific, Asia, and Latin America as well.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In order for digital agriculture to spread, national governments, multilateral organizations, and other policymakers must provide a clear regulatory framework so that stakeholders feel confident investing in digital agriculture solutions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Policy designed for the pre-Internet era prevents the advancement of "smart agriculture," as does regulatory ambiguity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Furthermore, a blurry line between personal and business data when discussing family farms complicates data regulation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Besides establishing regulations to boost stakeholder confidence, policymakers can harness digital agriculture for the provision of public goods.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] First, the United Nations' Global Open Data for Agriculture and Nutrition (GODAN) calls for open access to agricultural data as a basic right.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Rather than stakeholders operating in "data silos," where no one shares information for fear of competition, open data sources (when appropriately anonymized) can foster collaboration and innovation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Open-sourced data can rebalance the power asymmetry between farmers and large agribusinesses who collect data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Second, governments can finance research and development of digital agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Governments can also engage in private-public R&D partnerships to foster smallholder-oriented digital agriculture projects in developing countries.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Lastly, digital agriculture technologies, particularly traceability systems, can improve monitoring of environmental compliance, evaluation of subsidy eligibility, etc.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Finally, when governments and international undertake complementary investments, they can strengthen the enabling environment for digital agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] By improving digital infrastructure, choosing digital agriculture technologies appropriate for the regional context, and investing in human capital/digital skills development, policymakers could support digital agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] In the United States, research in digital agriculture is primarily funded by the National Institute of Food and Agriculture (NIFA) which comes under the US Department of Agriculture and to a lesser extent, by the National Science Foundation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Two large institutes applying IoT or artificial intelligence in digital agriculture have been unveiled by these funding organizations working together.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] According to Project Breakthrough, digital agriculture can help advance the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals by providing farmers with more real-time information about their farms, allowing them to make better decisions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Technology improves crop production by providing a better understanding of soil health.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] It allows farmers to use fewer pesticides on their crops.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Soil and weather monitoring reduces water waste.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture can lead to economic growth by allowing farmers to get the most production out of their land.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] The loss of agricultural jobs can be offset by new job opportunities in manufacturing and maintaining the necessary technology for the work.
[src:smart-farming-iot/digital-agriculture] Digital agriculture also enables individual farmers to work in concert, collecting and sharing data using technology.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:smart-farming-iot/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] In the 18th century, Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulfate) as a fertilizer.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] In 1843, John Bennet Lawes and Joseph Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term field experiments at Rothamsted Research in England, some of which are still running as of 2018.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] In the United States, a scientific revolution in agriculture began with the Hatch Act of 1887, which used the term "agricultural science".
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] The Hatch Act was driven by farmers' interest in knowing the constituents of early artificial fertilizer.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] The Smith–Hughes Act of 1917 shifted agricultural education back to its vocational roots, but the scientific foundation had been built.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] For the next 44 years after 1906, federal expenditures on agricultural research in the United States outpaced private expenditures.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] Climate change has had significant effects on modern agriculture, making weather patterns less predictable and increasing the frequency and intensity of extreme events such as prolonged droughts, floods and heatwaves.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] As a result, crop production has become more uncertain even in regions that were previously characterised by relatively stable climatic conditions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] Changes in temperature and rainfall regimes are also contributing to soil erosion, desertification and the degradation of water resources, with implications for long-term agricultural productivity and rural livelihoods.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] To address these issues, there has been increasing interest in agricultural research and practice in the so-called climate-smart strategies aimed at adapting agricultural systems to the existing and the forecasted climate effects and the minimisation of greenhouse gas emissions wherever feasible.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] These measures involve more efficient use of water and nutrients, crop and agriculture system diversification, soil and water protection, and creating crops and livestock strains more resistant to heat and drought among other challenges.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] The thrust of these endeavors defines the fundamental importance of agricultural science to the maintenance of food production, safeguarding natural resources and promoting resilience to environmental change.
[src:smart-farming-iot/farm-management] Agriculture, agricultural science, and agronomy are closely related.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The field has evolved due to the convergence of multiple technologies, including ubiquitous computing, sensors, embedded systems, and machine learning.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Traditional fields of embedded systems, wireless sensor networks, control systems, and automation independently and collectively enable the Internet of things.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] While in the consumer market, IoT technology is most commonly as smart home products—including devices and appliances like thermostats and smart speakers—the technology's largest applications are in the business and industrial sectors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Commercial asset tracking and fleet management represent the largest single application of IoT, accounting for 22% of the total market, driven by the need to monitor mobile assets like vehicles and shipping containers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The largest asset tracking sub-segments in transport & logistics are trailer and intermodal container tracking, reaching 5.8 million and 5.3 million active devices globally at the end of 2024 respectively.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Other major applications include industrial monitoring, smart metering in utilities, and connected healthcare.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Due to their interconnected nature, IoT devices are vulnerable to security breaches and privacy concerns.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] At the same time, the way these devices communicate wirelessly creates regulatory ambiguities, complicating jurisdictional boundaries of the data transfer.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Around 1972, for its remote site use, the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory developed a computer-controlled vending machine, adapted from a machine rented from Canteen Vending, which sold for cash or, through a computer terminal (Teletype Model 33 KSR), on credit.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Amongst its products were beer, yogurt, and milk.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It was named *Prancing Pony*, after the name of the room, which was named after an inn in J.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Tolkien's epic fantasy novel The Lord of the Rings.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] A successor version still operates in the Computer Science Department at Stanford, with updated hardware and software.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] While it was initially accessible only on the CMU campus, it gained prominence as the first ARPANET-connected appliance.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Mark Weiser's 1991 paper on ubiquitous computing, "The Computer of the 21st Century", as well as academic venues such as UbiComp and PerCom, produced the contemporary vision of the IoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The field gained momentum when Bill Joy envisioned device-to-device communication as part of his "Six Webs" framework, which was presented at the World Economic Forum in Davos in 1999.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The concept of the "Internet of things" and the term itself first appeared in a speech by Peter T.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Lewis to the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation 15th Annual Legislative Weekend in Washington, D.C., published in September 1985.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The primary defining characteristic of the Internet of things has been considered its ability to embed short-range mobile transceivers in various gadgets and daily necessities, enabling new forms of communication between people and things, as well as between things themselves.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Defining the Internet of things as "simply the point in time when more 'things or objects' were connected to the Internet than people", Cisco Systems estimated that the IoT was "born" between 2008 and 2009, with the things/people ratio growing from 0.08 in 2003 to 1.84 in 2010.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The extensive set of applications for IoT devices is often divided into consumer, commercial, industrial, and infrastructure spaces.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] A growing portion of IoT devices is created for consumer use, including connected vehicles, home automation, wearable technology, connected health, and appliances with remote monitoring capabilities.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are part of the broader concept of home automation, which generally includes lighting, heating and air conditioning, media and security systems, and camera systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, long-term benefits could include energy savings by automatically ensuring lights and electronics are turned off or by making the residents in the home aware of usage.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] A smart home, also known as an automated home, could be based on a platform or hubs that control smart devices and appliances.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] For instance, using Apple's HomeKit, manufacturers can have their home products and accessories controlled by an application in iOS devices such as the iPhone and the Apple Watch.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] This could be a dedicated app or iOS native applications such as Siri.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of Lenovo's Smart Home Essentials, which is a line of smart home devices that are controlled through Apple's Home app or Siri without the need for a Wi-Fi bridge.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] There are also dedicated smart home hubs that are offered as standalone platforms to connect different smart home products.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] These include the Amazon Echo, Google Home, Apple's HomePod, and Samsung's SmartThings Hub.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to the commercial systems, there are many non-proprietary, open source ecosystems, including Home Assistant, OpenHAB, and Domoticz.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] One key application of a smart home is to assist the elderly and individuals with disabilities.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] These home systems use assistive technology to accommodate an owner's specific disabilities.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Voice control can assist users with sight and mobility limitations while alert systems can be connected directly to cochlear implants worn by individuals with hearing impairments.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] They can also be equipped with additional safety features, including sensors that monitor for medical emergencies such as falls or seizures.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Smart home technology applied in this way can provide users with more freedom and a higher quality of life.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Enterprise IoT" refers to devices used in business and corporate settings.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Medical Things** (**IoMT**) is an application of the IoT for medical and health-related purposes, data collection and analysis for research, and monitoring.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The IoMT has been referenced as "Smart Healthcare", as the technology for creating a digitized healthcare system, connecting available medical resources and healthcare services.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to enable remote health monitoring and emergency notification systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] These health monitoring devices can range from blood pressure and heart rate monitors to advanced devices capable of monitoring specialized implants, such as pacemakers, Fitbit electronic wristbands, or advanced hearing aids.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Some hospitals have begun implementing "smart beds" that can detect when they are occupied and when a patient is attempting to get up.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It can also adjust itself to ensure appropriate pressure and support are applied to the patient without the manual interaction of nurses.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Specialized sensors can also be equipped within living spaces to monitor the health and general well-being of senior citizens, while ensuring that proper treatment is administered and assisting people in regaining lost mobility via therapy as well.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors create a network of intelligent sensors that are able to collect, process, transfer, and analyze valuable information in different environments, such as connecting in-home monitoring devices to hospital-based systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Other consumer devices to encourage healthy living, such as connected scales or wearable heart monitors, are also a possibility with the IoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] End-to-end health monitoring IoT platforms are also available for antenatal and chronic patients, helping one manage health vitals and recurring medication requirements.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Advances in plastic and fabric electronics fabrication methods have enabled ultra-low-cost, use-and-throw IoMT sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors, along with the required radio-frequency identification electronics, can be fabricated on paper or e-textiles for wireless powered disposable sensing devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Applications have been established for point-of-care medical diagnostics, where portability and low system complexity are considered essential.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] As of 2018, IoMT was being applied in the clinical laboratory industry.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoMT in the insurance industry provides access to better and new types of dynamic information.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] This includes sensor-based solutions such as biosensors, wearables, connected health devices, and mobile apps to track customer behavior.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] This can lead to more accurate underwriting and new pricing models.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The application of the IoT in healthcare plays a fundamental role in managing chronic diseases and in disease prevention and control.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Remote monitoring is made possible through the connection of wireless solutions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The connectivity enables health practitioners to capture patients' data and apply algorithms in health data analysis.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can assist in the integration of communications, control, and information processing across various transportation systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Application of the IoT extends to all aspects of transportation systems (i.e., the vehicle, the infrastructure, and the driver or user).
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Dynamic interaction between these components of a transport system enables inter- and intra-vehicular communication, smart traffic control, smart parking, electronic toll collection systems, logistics and fleet management, vehicle control, safety, and road assistance.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicle security applications, IoT-connected GPS trackers can operate for months or years on internal batteries, using low-power wide-area network protocols such as LTE-M to transmit location data to owners via smartphone applications when unauthorized movement is detected.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicular communication systems, vehicle-to-everything communication (V2X), consists of three main components: vehicle-to-vehicle communication (V2V), vehicle-to-infrastructure communication (V2I), and vehicle-to-pedestrian communication (V2P).
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Eventually, V2X is the first step to autonomous driving and connected road infrastructure.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to monitor and control the mechanical, electrical, and electronic systems used in various types of buildings (e.g., public and private, industrial, institutions, or residential) in home automation and building automation systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Also known as IIoT, industrial IoT devices acquire and analyze data from connected equipment, operational technology (OT), locations, and people.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Combined with operational technology (OT) monitoring devices, IIoT helps regulate and monitor industrial systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, the same implementation can be carried out for automated record updates of asset placement in industrial storage units as the size of the assets can vary from a small screw to the whole motor spare part, and misplacement of such assets can cause a loss of manpower time and money.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can connect various manufacturing devices equipped with sensing, identification, processing, communication, actuation, and networking capabilities.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Network control and management of manufacturing equipment, asset and situation management, or manufacturing process control enable IoT to be utilized for industrial applications and smart manufacturing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligent systems enable rapid manufacturing and optimization of new products and rapid response to product demands.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Digital control systems, which aim to automate process controls, operator tools, and service information systems, alongside optimizing plant safety and security, fall within the purview of the IIoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Furthermore, IoT can also be applied to asset management via predictive maintenance, statistical evaluation, and measurements to maximize reliability.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Industrial management systems can be integrated with smart grids, enabling energy optimization.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Measurements, automated controls, plant optimization, health and safety management, and other functions are provided by networked sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to general manufacturing, IoT is also used for processes in the industrialization of construction.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] There are numerous IoT applications in farming such as collecting data on temperature, rainfall, humidity, wind speed, pest infestation, and soil content.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] This data can be used to automate farming techniques, make informed decisions to improve quality and quantity, minimize risk and waste, and reduce the effort required to manage crops.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] For example, farmers can now monitor soil temperature and moisture from afar and even apply IoT-acquired data to precision fertilization programs.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The overall goal is that data from sensors, coupled with the farmer's knowledge and intuition about his or her farm, can help increase farm productivity, and also help reduce costs.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for IoT technologies related to water management.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The FarmBeats project from Microsoft Research that uses TV white space to connect farms is also a part of the Azure Marketplace now.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are in use to monitor the environments and systems of boats and yachts.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Many pleasure boats are left unattended for days in summer, and months in winter so such devices provide valuable early alerts of boat flooding, fire, and deep discharge of batteries.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Monitoring and controlling operations of sustainable urban and rural infrastructures like bridges, railway tracks and on- and offshore wind farms is a key application of the IoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT infrastructure can be used for monitoring any events or changes in structural conditions that can compromise safety and increase risk.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can benefit the construction industry by cost-saving, time reduction, better quality workday, paperless workflow and increase in productivity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It can help in making faster decisions and saving money in Real-Time Data Analytics.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It can also be used for scheduling repair and maintenance activities efficiently, by coordinating tasks between different service providers and users of these facilities.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can also be used to control critical infrastructure, like bridges, to provide access to ships.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The usage of IoT devices for monitoring and operating infrastructure is likely to significantly improve incident management and emergency response coordination, and quality of service, up-times and reduce costs of operation in all infrastructure-related areas.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Even areas such as waste management can benefit.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] There are several planned or ongoing large-scale deployments of the IoT to enable better management of cities and systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] For example, Songdo, South Korea, the first fully equipped and wired smart city, is gradually being built, with approximately 70 percent of the business district completed as of June 2018.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] A sizeable portion of the city, the first of its kind, is planned to be wired and automated to operate with little or no human intervention.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In 2014, another application was undergoing a project in Santander, Spain.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] For this deployment, two approaches have been adopted.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] This city of 180,000 inhabitants has already seen 18,000 downloads of its city smartphone app.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The app is connected to 10,000 sensors that enable services like parking search and environmental monitoring.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, city context information is used in this deployment, aiming to benefit merchants through a spark deals mechanism based on city behavior that aims at maximizing the impact of each notification.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Other examples of large-scale deployments underway include the Sino-Singapore Guangzhou Knowledge City; work on improving air and water quality, reducing noise pollution, and increasing transportation efficiency in San Jose, California; and smart traffic management in western Singapore.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Using its RPMA (Random Phase Multiple Access) technology, San Diego–based Ingenu has built a nationwide public network for low-bandwidth data transmissions using the same unlicensed 2.4 gigahertz spectrum as Wi-Fi.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Ingenu's "Machine Network" covers more than a third of the US population across 35 major cities including San Diego and Dallas.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] French company, Sigfox, commenced building an Ultra Narrowband wireless data network in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2014, the first business to achieve such a deployment in the U.S.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It subsequently announced it would set up a total of 4000 base stations to cover a total of 30 cities in the U.S. by the end of 2016, making it the largest IoT network coverage provider in the country thus far.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco also participates in smart cities projects.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco has deployed technologies for Smart Wi-Fi, Smart Safety & Security, Smart Lighting, Smart Parking, Smart Transports, Smart Bus Stops, Smart Kiosks, Remote Expert for Government Services (REGS) and Smart Education in the five km area in the city of Vijayawada, India.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of a large deployment is the one completed by New York Waterways in New York City to connect all the city's vessels and be able to monitor them live 24/7.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The network was designed and engineered by Fluidmesh Networks, a Chicago-based company developing wireless networks for critical applications.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The NYWW network is currently providing coverage on the Hudson River, East River, and Upper New York Bay.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] With the wireless network in place, NY Waterway is able to take control of its fleet and passengers in a way that was not previously possible.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] New applications can include security, energy and fleet management, digital signage, public Wi-Fi, paperless ticketing and others.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Significant numbers of energy-consuming devices (e.g., lamps, household appliances, motors, pumps, etc.) already integrate Internet connectivity, which can allow them to communicate with utilities not only to balance power generation but also helps optimize the energy consumption as a whole.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] These devices allow for remote control by users, or central management via a cloud-based interface, and enable functions like scheduling (e.g., remotely powering on or off heating systems, controlling ovens, changing lighting conditions etc.).
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The smart grid is a utility-side IoT application; systems gather and act on energy and power-related information to improve the efficiency of the production and distribution of electricity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) Internet-connected devices, electric utilities not only collect data from end-users, but also manage distribution automation devices like transformers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Environmental monitoring applications of the IoT typically use sensors to assist in environmental protection by monitoring air or water quality, atmospheric or soil conditions, and can even include areas like monitoring the movements of wildlife and their habitats.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Development of resource-constrained devices connected to the Internet also means that other applications like earthquake or tsunami early-warning systems can also be used by emergency services to provide more effective aid.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices in this application typically span a large geographic area and can also be mobile.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It has been argued that the standardization that IoT brings to wireless sensing will revolutionize this area.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of integrating the IoT is the concept of a "living lab." Living labs integrate and combine research and innovation processes, establishing within a public-private-people-partnership.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Between 2006 and January 2024, there were over 440 living labs (though not all are currently active) that use the IoT to collaborate and share knowledge between stakeholders to co-create innovative and technological products.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] When companies intend to implement and develop IoT services for smart cities, they need to have economic incentives.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The US government plays a key role in smart city projects; changes in policies will help cities to implement the IoT, which provides effectiveness, efficiency, and accuracy of the resources that are being used.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The Internet of Military Things (IoMT) is the application of IoT technologies in the military domain for the purposes of reconnaissance, surveillance, and other combat-related objectives.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It is heavily influenced by the future prospects of warfare in an urban environment and involves the use of sensors, munitions, vehicles, robots, human-wearable biometrics, and other smart technology that is relevant on the battlefield.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] One of the examples of IOT devices used in the military is the Xaver 1000 system.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The Xaver 1000 was developed by Israel's Camero Tech, which is the latest in the company's line of "through-wall imaging systems." The Xaver line uses millimeter wave (MMW) radar, or radar in the range of 30-300 gigahertz.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It is equipped with an AI-based life target tracking system as well as its own 3D 'sense-through-the-wall' technology.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Battlefield Things** (**IoBT**) is a project initiated and executed by the U.S.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) that focuses on the basic science related to the IoT that enhances the capabilities of Army soldiers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In 2017, ARL launched the Internet of Battlefield Things Collaborative Research Alliance (IoBT-CRA), establishing a working collaboration between industry, university, and Army researchers to advance the theoretical foundations of IoT technologies and their applications to Army operations.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The **Ocean of Things** project is a DARPA-led program designed to establish an Internet of things across large ocean areas for the purposes of collecting, monitoring, and analyzing environmental and vessel activity data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The project entails the deployment of about 50,000 floats that house a passive sensor suite that autonomously detects and tracks military and commercial vessels as part of a cloud-based network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] There are several applications of smart or active packaging in which a QR code or NFC tag is affixed to a product or its packaging.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The tag itself is passive; however, it contains a unique identifier (typically a URL) which enables a user to access digital content about the product via a smartphone.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Strictly speaking, such passive items are not part of the Internet of things, but they can be seen as enablers of digital interactions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Internet of Packaging" has been coined to describe applications in which unique identifiers are used, to automate supply chains, and are scanned on large scale by consumers to access digital content.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Authentication of the unique identifiers, and thereby of the product itself, is possible via a copy-sensitive digital watermark or copy detection pattern for scanning when scanning a QR code, while NFC tags can encrypt communication.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of Things (IoT), As of April 2026, the number of devices connected and controlled via the Internet has increased.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Applications of IoT technology vary across devices, but many share common characteristics.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, resulting in efficiency improvements, economic benefits, and reduced human exertions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT Analytics reported there were 16.6 billion IoT devices connected in 2023.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In 2020, the same firm projected there would be 30 billion devices connected by 2025.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] As of October, 2024, there are around 17 billion.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control are not part of the original concept of the Internet of things.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control do not necessarily require Internet structures, either.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] However, there is a shift in research (by companies such as Intel) to integrate the concepts of the IoT and autonomous control, with initial outcomes towards this direction considering objects as the driving force for autonomous IoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] An approach in this context is deep reinforcement learning where most of IoT systems provide a dynamic and interactive environment.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Training an agent (i.e., IoT device) to behave smartly in such an environment cannot be addressed by conventional machine learning algorithms such as supervised learning.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Through a reinforcement learning approach, a learning agent can sense the environment's state (e.g., sensing home temperature), perform actions (e.g., turn HVAC on or off) and learn by maximizing accumulated rewards it receives.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligence can be offered at three levels: IoT devices, Edge/Fog nodes, and cloud computing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The need for intelligent control and decision at each level depends on the time sensitiveness of the IoT application.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] For example, an autonomous vehicle's camera needs to make real-time obstacle detection to avoid an accident.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] This fast decision making would not be possible if it is necessary to transfer data from the vehicle to cloud instances and return the predictions back to the vehicle.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Instead, the operation should be performed locally in the vehicle.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Integrating advanced machine learning algorithms, including deep learning, into IoT devices is an active research area to make smart objects closer to reality.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, it is possible to get the most value out of IoT deployments through analyzing IoT data, extracting hidden information, and predicting control decisions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] A wide variety of machine learning techniques have been used in IoT domain ranging from traditional methods such as regression, support vector machine, and random forest to advanced ones such as convolutional neural networks, LSTM, and variational autoencoder.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Modern IoT products and solutions in the marketplace use a variety of different technologies to support such context-aware automation, but more sophisticated forms of intelligence are requested to permit sensor units and intelligent cyber-physical systems to be deployed in real environments.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT system architecture, in its simplistic view, consists of three tiers: Tier 1: Devices, Tier 2: the Edge Gateway, and Tier 3: the Cloud.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Devices include networked things, such as the sensors and actuators found in IoT equipment, particularly those that use protocols such as Modbus, Bluetooth, Zigbee, or proprietary protocols, to connect to an Edge Gateway.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The Edge Gateway layer consists of sensor data aggregation systems called Edge Gateways that provide functionality, such as pre-processing of the data, securing connectivity to cloud, using systems such as WebSockets, the event hub, and, even in some cases, edge analytics or fog computing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Edge Gateway layer is also required to give a common view of the devices to the upper layers to facilitate in easier management.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The final tier includes the cloud application built for IoT using the microservices architecture, which are usually polyglot and inherently secure in nature using HTTPS/OAuth.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] It includes various database systems that store sensor data, such as time series databases or asset stores using backend data storage systems (e.g.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The cloud tier in most cloud-based IoT system features event queuing and messaging system that handles communication that transpires in all tiers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Some experts classified the three-tiers in the IoT system as edge, platform, and enterprise and these are connected by proximity network, access network, and service network, respectively.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT requires huge scalability in the network space to handle the surge of devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IETF 6LoWPAN can be used to connect devices to IP networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] With billions of devices being added to the Internet space, IPv6 may play an important role in handling the network layer scalability.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IETF's Constrained Application Protocol, ZeroMQ, and MQTT can provide lightweight data transport.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In practice, many groups of IoT devices are hidden behind gateway nodes and may not have unique addresses.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Also, the vision of everything being interconnected is not needed for most applications as it is mainly the data that needs interconnecting at a higher layer.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Fog computing is a viable alternative to prevent such a large burst of data flow through the Internet.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The edge devices' computation power to analyze and process data is extremely limited.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Limited processing power is a key attribute of IoT devices as their purpose is to supply data about physical objects while remaining autonomous.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Heavy processing requirements use more battery power, harming IoT's ability to operate.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Scalability is easy because IoT devices simply supply data through the Internet to a server with sufficient processing power.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Performance is improved, especially for huge IoT systems with millions of nodes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Conventional IoT is connected via a mesh network and led by a major head node (centralized controller).
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The head node decides how a data is created, stored, and transmitted.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In contrast, decentralized IoT attempts to divide IoT systems into smaller divisions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The head node authorizes partial decision-making power to lower level sub-nodes under mutual agreed policy.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Some approaches to decentralized IoT attempt to address the limited bandwidth and hashing capacity of battery-powered or wireless IoT devices via blockchain.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In semi-open or closed loops (i.e., value chains, whenever a global finality can be settled) the IoT is often analyzed as a complex system due to the large number of different interactions between autonomous actors, and its capacity to integrate new actors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] At the overall stage (full open loop) it will likely be seen as a chaotic environment (since systems always have finality).
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] As a practical approach, not all elements on the Internet of things run in a global, public space.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Subsystems are often implemented to mitigate the risks of privacy, control and reliability.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] For example, domestic robotics (domotics) running inside a smart home might only share data within and be available via a local network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Managing and controlling a high dynamic ad hoc IoT things/devices network is a complex task within traditional network architecture, software-defined networking (SDN) provides a dynamic approach that better fits the special requirements of IoT applications.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The exact scale of the Internet of things is unknown, with quotes of billions or trillions often quoted at the beginning of IoT articles.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In 2015, there were 83 million smart devices in people's homes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] This number is expected to grow to 193 million devices by 2020.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In 2023, the number of connected IoT devices will reach 16.6 billion.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] The number of online-capable devices grew 31% from 2016 to 2017 to reach 8.4 billion.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of things, the precise geographic location of a thing—and also the precise geographic dimensions of a thing—can be critical.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] (Note that some things on the Internet of things will be sensors, and sensor location is usually important.) The GeoWeb and Digital Earth are applications that become possible when things can become organized and connected by location.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] However, the challenges that remain include the constraints of variable spatial scales, the need to handle massive amounts of data, and an indexing for fast search and neighbour operations.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] On the Internet of things, if things are able to take actions on their own initiative, this human-centric mediation role is eliminated.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Thus, the time-space context that we as humans take for granted must be given a central role in this information ecosystem.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Just as standards play a key role on the Internet and the Web, geo-spatial standards will play a key role on the Internet of things.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Many IoT devices have the potential to take a piece of this market.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] For improved user interaction, some technology leaders are joining forces to create standards for communication between devices to solve this problem.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Others are turning to the concept of predictive interaction of devices, "where collected data is used to predict and trigger actions on the specific devices" while making them work together.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Social Internet of things (SIoT) is a new kind of IoT that focuses on the importance of social interaction and relationships between IoT devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT defines a device with an identity like a citizen in a community and connects them to the Internet to provide services to its users.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT defines a social network for IoT devices only to interact with each other for different goals that to serve human.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is different from the original IoT in terms of the collaboration characteristics.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT is passive; it was set to serve for dedicated purposes with existing IoT devices in a predetermined system.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is active, it was programmed and managed by AI to serve for unplanned purposes with mix and match of potential IoT devices from different systems that benefit its users.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices with built-in sociability are able to broadcast their abilities or functionality, which can be used to discover and share information with other IoT devices in the same or nearby network, realizing SIoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Facilitating further functionality with these abilities could be helpful during emergencies.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] IoT sensors on the vehicles, road and traffic lights monitor the conditions of the vehicles and drivers and alert when attention is needed, and also coordinate themselves automatically to ensure autonomous driving is working normally.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] If a crash happens, the IoT camera will inform the nearest hospital and police station for help.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] System security is always a concern for any technology, and it is more crucial for SIoT as not only the security of oneself needs to be considered, but also the mutual trust mechanism between collaborative IoT devices from time to time, from place to place.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] Another critical challenge for SIoT is the accuracy and reliability of the sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p01] In most circumstances, IoT sensors would need to respond quickly to avoid accidents, injury, and loss of life.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] There are many technologies that enable the IoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The original idea of the Auto-ID Center is based on RFID tags and distinct identification through the Electronic Product Code.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This has evolved into objects having an IP address or URI.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] An alternative view, from the world of the Semantic Web focuses instead on making all things (not just those electronic, smart, or RFID-enabled) addressable by the existing naming protocols, such as URI.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The objects themselves do not converse, but they may now be referred to by other agents, such as powerful centralised servers acting for their human owners.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Integration with the Internet implies that devices will use an IP address as a distinct identifier.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Due to the limited address space of IPv4 (which allows for 4.3 billion different addresses), objects in the IoT will have to use the next generation of the Internet protocol (IPv6) to scale to the extremely large address space required.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Internet-of-things devices additionally will benefit from the stateless address auto-configuration present in IPv6, as it reduces the configuration overhead on the hosts, and the IETF 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] To a large extent, the future of the Internet of things will not be possible without the support of IPv6; and consequently, the global adoption of IPv6 in the coming years will be critical for the successful development of the IoT in the future.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Different technologies have different roles in a protocol stack.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This is a list of technical standards for the IoT, most of which are open standards, and the standards organizations that aspire to successfully setting them.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Some scholars and activists argue that the IoT can be used to create new models of civic engagement if device networks can be open to user control and interoperable platforms.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that political life in both democracies and authoritarian regimes will be shaped by the way the IoT will be used for civic engagement.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] For that to happen, he argues that any connected device should be able to divulge a list of the "ultimate beneficiaries" of its sensor data and that individual citizens should be able to add new organisations to the beneficiary list.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, he argues that civil society groups need to start developing their IoT strategy for making use of data and engaging with the public.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] One of the key drivers of the IoT is data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The success of the idea of connecting devices to make them more efficient is dependent upon access to and storage & processing of data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] For this purpose, companies working on the IoT collect data from multiple sources and store it in their cloud network for further processing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This leaves the door wide open for privacy and security dangers and single point vulnerability of multiple systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The other issues pertain to consumer choice and ownership of data and how it is used.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Though still in their infancy, regulations and governance regarding these issues of privacy, security, and data ownership continue to develop.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Some examples of legislation that is relevant to privacy and data collection are: the US Privacy Act of 1974, OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy and Transborder Flows of Personal Data of 1980, and the EU Directive 95/46/EC of 1995.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] However, the FTC stopped at just making recommendations for now.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] A resolution passed by the Senate in March 2015, is already being considered by the Congress.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This resolution recognized the need for formulating a National Policy on IoT and the matter of privacy, security and spectrum.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Approved on 28 September 2018, California Senate Bill No.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Several standards for the IoT industry are actually being established relating to automobiles because most concerns arising from use of connected cars apply to healthcare devices as well.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In fact, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) is preparing cybersecurity guidelines and a database of best practices to make automotive computer systems more secure.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] A recent report from the World Bank examines the challenges and opportunities in government adoption of IoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In early December 2021, the U.K. government introduced the Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure bill (PST), an effort to legislate IoT distributors, manufacturers, and importers to meet certain cybersecurity standards.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The bill also seeks to improve the security credentials of consumer IoT devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] For example, wireless connectivity for IoT devices can be done using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi HaLow, Zigbee, Z-Wave, LoRa, NB-IoT, Cat M1 as well as completely custom proprietary radios – each with its own advantages and disadvantages; and unique support ecosystem.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The IoT's amorphous computing nature is also a problem for security, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] One set of researchers says that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active Android devices vulnerable.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that the Internet of things offers immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Concerns about privacy have led many to consider the possibility that big data infrastructures such as the Internet of things and data mining are inherently incompatible with privacy.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Key challenges of increased digitalization in the water, transport or energy sector are related to privacy and cybersecurity which necessitate an adequate response from research and policymakers alike.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Writer Adam Greenfield claims that IoT technologies are not only an invasion of public space but are also being used to perpetuate normative behavior, citing an instance of billboards with hidden cameras that tracked the demographics of passersby who stopped to read the advertisement.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Council compared the increased prevalence of digital surveillance due to the Internet of things to the concept of the panopticon described by Jeremy Bentham in the 18th century.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The assertion is supported by the works of French philosophers Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In *Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison*, Foucault asserts that the panopticon was a central element of the discipline society developed during the Industrial Era.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Foucault also argued that the discipline systems established in factories and school reflected Bentham's vision of panopticism.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In his 1992 paper "Postscripts on the Societies of Control", Deleuze wrote that the discipline society had transitioned into a control society, with the computer replacing the panopticon as an instrument of discipline and control while still maintaining the qualities similar to that of panopticism.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Peter-Paul Verbeek, a professor of philosophy of technology at the University of Twente, Netherlands, writes that technology already influences our moral decision making, which in turn affects human agency, privacy and autonomy.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] He cautions against viewing technology merely as a human tool and advocates instead to consider it as an active agent.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Tim O'Reilly believes that the way companies sell IoT devices to consumers is misplaced, disputing the notion that the IoT is about gaining efficiency from putting all kinds of devices online and postulating that, "IoT is really about human augmentation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Editorials at WIRED have also expressed concern, one stating, "What you're about to lose is your privacy.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) expressed concern regarding the ability of IoT to erode people's control over their own lives.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The ACLU wrote that "There's simply no way to forecast how these immense powers – disproportionately accumulating in the hands of corporations seeking financial advantage and governments craving ever more control – will be used.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In response to rising concerns about privacy and smart technology, in 2007, the British Government stated it would follow formal Privacy by Design principles when implementing its smart metering program.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The program would lead to the replacement of traditional power meters with smart power meters, which could track and manage energy usage more accurately.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] However the British Computer Society is doubtful these principles were ever actually implemented.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In 2009, the Dutch Parliament rejected a similar smart metering program, basing their decision on privacy concerns.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The Dutch program later revised and passed in 2011.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] A challenge for producers of IoT applications is to clean, process and interpret the vast amount of data that is gathered by the sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] There is a solution proposed for the analytics of the information referred to as Wireless Sensor Networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] These networks share data among sensor nodes that are sent to a distributed system for the analytics of the sensory data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Another challenge is the storage of this bulk data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Depending on the application, there could be high data acquisition requirements, which in turn lead to high storage requirements.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In 2013, the Internet was estimated to be responsible for consuming 5% of the total energy produced, and a "daunting challenge to power" IoT devices to collect and even store data still remains.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Data silos, although a common challenge of legacy systems, still commonly occur with the implementation of IoT devices, particularly within manufacturing.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] As there are a lot of benefits to be gained from IoT and IIoT devices, the means in which the data is stored can present serious challenges without the principles of autonomy, transparency, and interoperability being considered.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The challenges do not occur by the device itself, but the means in which databases and data warehouses are set up.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] These challenges were identified by Keller (2021) when investigating the IT and application landscape of I4.0 implementation within German M&E manufacturers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Security is the biggest concern in adopting Internet of things technology, with concerns that rapid development is happening without appropriate consideration of the profound security challenges involved and the regulatory changes that might be necessary.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The rapid development of the Internet of Things (IoT) has allowed billions of devices to connect to the network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Due to too many connected devices and the limitation of communication security technology, various security issues gradually appear in the IoT.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Most of the technical security concerns are similar to those of conventional servers, workstations and smartphones.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] These concerns include using weak authentication, forgetting to change default credentials, unencrypted messages sent between devices, SQL injections, man-in-the-middle attacks, and poor handling of security updates.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] However, many IoT devices have severe operational limitations on the computational power available to them.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] These constraints often make them unable to directly use basic security measures such as implementing firewalls or using strong cryptosystems to encrypt their communications with other devices - and the low price and consumer focus of many devices makes a robust security patching system uncommon.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Rather than conventional security vulnerabilities, fault injection attacks are on the rise and targeting IoT devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] A fault injection attack is a physical attack on a device to purposefully introduce faults in the system to change the intended behavior.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Faults might happen unintentionally due to environmental noises and electromagnetic fields.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] There are ideas stemming from control-flow integrity (CFI) to prevent fault injection attacks and system recovery to a healthy state before the fault.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Computer-controlled devices in automobiles such as brakes, engine, locks, hood and trunk releases, horn, heat, and dashboard have been shown to be vulnerable to attackers who have access to the on-board network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In some cases, vehicle computer systems are Internet-connected, allowing them to be exploited remotely.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] By 2008, security researchers had shown the ability to remotely control pacemakers without authority.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Later, hackers demonstrated remote control of insulin pumps and implantable cardioverter defibrillators.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Poorly secured Internet-accessible IoT devices can also be subverted to attack others.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In 2016, a distributed denial of service attack powered by Internet of things devices running the Mirai malware took down a DNS provider and major web sites.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had infected roughly 65,000 IoT devices within the first 20 hours.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Eventually, the infections increased to around 200,000 to 300,000 infections.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Brazil, Colombia and Vietnam made up of 41.5% of the infections.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had singled out specific IoT devices that consisted of DVRs, IP cameras, routers and printers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] These sorts of attacks have caused security experts to view IoT as a real threat to Internet services.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] National Intelligence Council in an unclassified report maintains that it would be hard to deny "access to networks of sensors and remotely-controlled objects by enemies of the United States, criminals, and mischief makers...
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] An open market for aggregated sensor data could serve the interests of commerce and security no less than it helps criminals and spies identify vulnerable targets.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Thus, massively parallel sensor fusion may undermine social cohesion, if it proves to be fundamentally incompatible with Fourth-Amendment guarantees against unreasonable search." In general, the intelligence community views the Internet of things as a rich source of data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] There have been a range of responses to concerns over security.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Security Foundation (IoTSF) was launched on 23 September 2015 with a mission to secure the Internet of things by promoting knowledge and best practices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Its founding board is made up of technology providers and telecommunications companies.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, large IT companies are continually developing innovative solutions to ensure the security of IoT devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In 2017, Mozilla launched Project Things, which allows to route IoT devices through a safe Web of Things gateway.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] As per the estimates from KBV Research, the overall IoT security market would grow at 27.9% rate during 2016–2022 as a result of growing infrastructural concerns and diversified usage of Internet of things.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Governmental regulation is argued by some to be necessary to secure IoT devices and the wider Internet – as market incentives to secure IoT devices is insufficient.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] It was found that due to the nature of most of the IoT development boards, they generate predictable and weak keys which make it easy to be utilized by man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] However, various hardening approaches were proposed by many researchers to resolve the issue of SSH weak implementation and weak keys.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] IoT security within the field of manufacturing presents different challenges and varying perspectives.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Within the EU and Germany, data protection is constantly referenced throughout manufacturing and digital policy, particularly that of I4.0.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] However, the attitude towards data security differs from the enterprise perspective, whereas there is an emphasis on less data protection in the form of GDPR, as the data being collected from IoT devices in the manufacturing sector does not display personal details.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Yet, research has indicated that manufacturing experts are concerned about "data security for protecting machine technology from international competitors with the ever-greater push for interconnectivity".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] IoT systems are typically controlled by event-driven smart apps that take as input either sensed data, user inputs, or other external triggers (from the Internet) and command one or more actuators towards providing different forms of automation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of sensors include smoke detectors, motion sensors, and contact sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of actuators include smart locks, smart power outlets, and door controls.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Popular control platforms on which third-party developers can build smart apps that interact wirelessly with these sensors and actuators include Samsung's SmartThings, Apple's HomeKit, and Amazon's Alexa, among others.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Detecting flaws that lead to such states, requires a holistic view of installed apps, component devices, their configurations, and more importantly, how they interact.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Recently, researchers from the University of California Riverside have proposed IotSan, a novel practical system that uses model checking as a building block to reveal "interaction-level" flaws by identifying events that can lead the system to unsafe states.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] They have evaluated IotSan on the Samsung SmartThings platform.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] From 76 manually configured systems, IotSan detects 147 vulnerabilities (i.e., violations of safe physical states/properties).
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Given widespread recognition of the evolving nature of the design and management of the Internet of things, sustainable and secure deployment of IoT solutions must design for "anarchic scalability".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Application of the concept of anarchic scalability can be extended to physical systems (i.e. controlled real-world objects), by virtue of those systems being designed to account for uncertain management futures.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This hard anarchic scalability thus provides a pathway forward to fully realize the potential of Internet-of-things solutions by selectively constraining physical systems to allow for all management regimes without risking physical failure.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Brown University computer scientist Michael Littman has argued that successful execution of the Internet of things requires consideration of the interface's usability as well as the technology itself.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] A concern regarding Internet-of-things technologies pertains to the environmental impacts of the manufacture, use, and eventual disposal of all these semiconductor-rich devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Modern electronics are replete with a wide variety of heavy metals and rare-earth metals, as well as highly toxic synthetic chemicals.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This makes them extremely difficult to properly recycle.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Electronic components are often incinerated or placed in regular landfills.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Furthermore, the human and environmental cost of mining the rare-earth metals that are integral to modern electronic components continues to grow.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This leads to societal questions concerning the environmental impacts of IoT devices over their lifetime.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation has raised concerns that companies can use the technologies necessary to support connected devices to intentionally disable or "brick" their customers' devices via a remote software update or by disabling a service necessary to the operation of the device.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In one example, home automation devices sold with the promise of a "Lifetime Subscription" were rendered useless after Nest Labs acquired Revolv and made the decision to shut down the central servers the Revolv devices had used to operate.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Owners should be free to point their devices to a different server or collaborate on improved software.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] But such action violates the United States DMCA section 1201, which only has an exemption for "local use".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This forces tinkerers who want to keep using their own equipment into a legal grey area.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] EFF thinks buyers should refuse electronics and software that prioritize the manufacturer's wishes above their own.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of post-sale manipulations include Google Nest Revolv, disabled privacy settings on Android, Sony disabling Linux on PlayStation 3, and enforced EULA on Wii U.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Kevin Lonergan at *Information Age*, a business technology magazine, has referred to the terms surrounding the IoT as a "terminology zoo".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The lack of clear terminology is not "useful from a practical point of view" and a "source of confusion for the end user".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] A company operating in the IoT space could be working in anything related to sensor technology, networking, embedded systems, or analytics.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Regarding IIoT, an industrial sub-field of IoT, the Industrial Internet Consortium's Vocabulary Task Group has created a "common and reusable vocabulary of terms" to ensure "consistent terminology" across publications issued by the Industrial Internet Consortium.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] IoT One has created an IoT Terms Database including a New Term Alert to be notified when a new term is published.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] As of March 2020, this database aggregates 807 IoT-related terms, while keeping material "transparent and comprehensive".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Despite a shared belief in the potential of the IoT, industry leaders and consumers are facing barriers to adopting IoT technology more widely.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Mike Farley argued in Forbes that while IoT solutions appeal to early adopters, they either lack interoperability or a clear use case for end-users.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] A study by Ericsson regarding the adoption of IoT among Danish companies suggests that many struggle "to pinpoint exactly where the value of IoT lies for them".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] As for IoT, especially in regard to consumer IoT, information about a user's daily routine is collected so that the "things" around the user can cooperate to provide better services that fulfill personal preferences.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] When the collected information which describes a user in detail travels through multiple hops in a network, due to a diverse integration of services, devices and network, the information stored on a device is vulnerable to privacy violation by compromising nodes existing in an IoT network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] For example, on 21 October 2016, a multiple distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks systems operated by domain name system provider Dyn, which caused the inaccessibility of several websites, such as GitHub, Twitter, and others.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] This attack is executed through a botnet consisting of a large number of IoT devices including IP cameras, gateways, and even baby monitors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Information privacy regulations also require organisations to practice "reasonable security".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] As each organisation's environment is unique, it can prove challenging to demonstrate what "reasonable security" is and what potential risks could be involved for the business.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] According to antivirus provider Kaspersky, there were 639 million data breaches of IoT devices in 2020 and 1.5 billion breaches in the first six months of 2021.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] One method of overcoming the barrier of safety issues is the introduction of standards and certification of devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] In 2024, two voluntary and non-competing programs were proposed and launched in the United States: the US Cyber Trust Mark from The Federal Communications Commission and CSA's IoT Device Security Specification from the Connectivity Standards Alliance.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] The programs incorporate international expertise, with the CSA mark recognized by the Singapore Cybersecurity Agency.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Compliance means that IoT devices can resist hacking, control hijacking and theft of confidential data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Some of these companies risk being "kodaked" – "Kodak was a market leader until digital disruption eclipsed film photography with digital photos" – failing to "see the disruptive forces affecting their industry" and "to truly embrace the new business models the disruptive change opens up".
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] According to a 2018 study, 70–75% of IoT deployments were stuck in the pilot or prototype stage, unable to reach scale due in part to a lack of business planning.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Even though scientists, engineers, and managers across the world are continuously working to create and exploit the benefits of IoT products, there are some flaws in the governance, management and implementation of such projects.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Despite tremendous forward momentum in the field of information and other underlying technologies, IoT still remains a complex area and the problem of how IoT projects are managed still needs to be addressed.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] IoT projects must be run differently than simple and traditional IT, manufacturing or construction projects.
[src:smart-farming-iot/internet-of-things-p02] Because IoT projects have longer project timelines, a lack of skilled resources and several security/legal issues, there is a need for new and specifically designed project processes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] The technology is primarily used for applications where small amounts of data need to be transmitted infrequently from hard-to-reach locations.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] The technology covers the physical layer, while other technologies and protocols such as LoRaWAN cover the upper layers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] It can achieve data rates between 0.3 kbit/s and 27 kbit/s, depending upon the spreading factor.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] LoRa uses a proprietary spread spectrum modulation that is similar to and a derivative of chirp spread spectrum (CSS) modulation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] Each symbol is represented by a cyclic shifted chirp over the bandwidth centered around the base frequency.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] The spreading factor (SF) is a selectable radio parameter from 5 to 12 and represents the number of bits sent per symbol and in addition determines how much the information is spread over time.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] There are $M=2^{\mathrm {SF} }$ different initial frequencies of the cyclic shifted chirp across the bandwidth around the center frequency.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] The symbol rate is determined by $R_{s}=B/M$ .
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] LoRa can tradeoff data rate for sensitivity (assuming a fixed channel bandwidth B ) by selecting the SF, i.e. the amount of spread used.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] A lower SF corresponds to a higher data rate but a worse sensitivity, a higher SF implies a better sensitivity but a lower data rate.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] Compared to lower SF, sending the same amount of data with higher SF needs more transmission time, known as time-on-air.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] More time-on-air means that the modem is transmitting for a longer time and consuming more energy.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] Typical LoRa modems support transmit powers up to +22 dBm.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] However, the regulations of the respective country may additionally limit the allowed transmit power.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] Higher transmit power results in higher signal power at the receiver and hence a higher link budget, but at the cost of consuming more energy.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] There are measurement studies of LoRa performance with regard to energy consumption, communication distances, and medium access efficiency.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] According to the LoRa Development Portal, the range provided by LoRa can be up to 3 miles (4.8 km) in urban areas, and up to 10 miles (16 km) or more in rural areas (line of sight).
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] In addition, LoRa uses forward error correction coding to improve resilience against interference.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] LoRa's high range is characterized by high wireless link budgets of around 155 dB to 170 dB.
[src:smart-farming-iot/lora] Range extenders for LoRa are called LoRaX.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] A central component of implementing this strategy is the satellite monitoring of agricultural machinery, which forms the basis for modern farm fleet management.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This is achieved through the use of fleet telematics systems, where vehicles are equipped with a GPS tracking unit and an onboard controller that transmits telemetry data—such as location, speed, engine hours, and fuel consumption—to a central server for analysis.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This stream of real-time data allows for the automation of agricultural operations and provides critical insights for improving diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The practice of precision agriculture has been enabled by the advent of GPS and GNSS.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Similar data is collected by sensor arrays mounted on GPS-equipped combine harvesters.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] These arrays consist of real-time sensors that measure everything from chlorophyll levels to plant water status, along with multispectral imagery.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This data is used in conjunction with satellite imagery by variable rate technology (VRT) including seeders, sprayers, etc. to optimally distribute resources.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] However, recent technological advances have enabled the use of real-time sensors directly in soil, which can wirelessly transmit data without the need of human presence.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture can benefit from unmanned aerial vehicles, that are relatively inexpensive and can be operated by novice pilots.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] These agricultural drones can be equipped with multispectral or RGB cameras to capture many images of a field that can be stitched together using photogrammetric methods to create orthophotos.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] These multispectral images contain multiple values per pixel in addition to the traditional red, green blue values such as near infrared and red-edge spectrum values used to process and analyze vegetative indexes such as NDVI maps.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] These drones are capable of capturing imagery and providing additional geographical references such as elevation, which allows software to perform map algebra functions to build precise topography maps.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] These topographic maps can be used to correlate crop health with topography, the results of which can be used to optimize crop inputs such as water, fertilizer or chemicals such as herbicides and growth regulators through variable rate applications.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture is a key component of the third wave of modern agricultural revolutions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The first agricultural revolution was the increase of mechanized agriculture, from 1900 to 1930.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Each farmer produced enough food to feed about 26 people during this time.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The 1960s prompted the Green Revolution with new methods of genetic modification, which led to each farmer feeding about 156 people.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] It is expected that by 2050, the global population will reach about 9.6 billion, and food production must effectively double from current levels in order to feed every mouth.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] With new technological advancements in the agricultural revolution of precision farming, each farmer will be able to feed 265 people on the same acreage.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The first wave of the precision agricultural revolution came in the forms of satellite and aerial imagery, weather prediction, variable rate fertilizer application, and crop health indicators.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The second wave aggregates the machine data for even more precise planting, topographical mapping, and soil data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture uses many tools, but some of the basics include tractors, combines, sprayers, planters, and diggers, which are all considered auto-guidance systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The small devices on the equipment that use GIS (geographic information system) are what makes precision agriculture what it is; the GIS system can be thought of as the “brain”.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] To be able to use precision agriculture, the equipment needs to be wired with the right technology and data systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] More tools include Variable rate technology (VRT), Global positioning system, Geographical information system, Grid sampling, and remote sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Geolocating a field enables the farmer to overlay information gathered from the analysis of soils and residual nitrogen, and information on previous crops and soil resistivity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Intra and inter-field variability may result from a number of factors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] These include climatic conditions (hail, drought, rain, etc.), soils (texture, depth, nitrogen levels), cropping practices (no-till farming), weeds, and disease.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Permanent indicators—chiefly soil indicators—provide farmers with information about the main environmental constants.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Point indicators allow them to track a crop's status, i.e., to see whether diseases are developing, if the crop is suffering from water stress, nitrogen stress, or lodging, whether it has been damaged by ice, and so on.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This information may come from weather stations and other sensors (soil electrical resistivity, detection with the naked eye, satellite imagery, etc.).
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Soil resistivity measurements combined with soil analysis make it possible to measure moisture content.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Soil resistivity is also a relatively simple and cheap measurement.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] It is important to realize why PA technology is or is not adopted, "for PA technology adoption to occur the farmer has to perceive the technology as useful and easy to use.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] New information and communication technologies make field-level crop management more operational and easier to achieve for farmers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Application of crop management decisions calls for agricultural equipment that supports variable-rate technology (VRT), for example varying seed density along with the variable-rate application (VRA) of nitrogen and phytosanitary products.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The concept of precision agriculture first emerged in the United States in the early 1980s.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] In 1985, researchers at the University of Minnesota varied lime inputs in crop fields.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] It was also at this time that the practice of grid sampling appeared (applying a fixed grid of one sample per hectare).
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Towards the end of the 1980s, this technique was used to derive the first input recommendation maps for fertilizers and pH corrections.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The use of yield sensors developed from new technologies, combined with the advent of GPS receivers, has been gaining ground ever since.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Today, such systems cover several million hectares.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] In the American Midwest (US), it is associated not with sustainable agriculture but with mainstream farmers who are trying to maximize profits by spending money only in areas that require fertilizer.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This practice allows the farmer to vary the rate of fertilizer across the field according to the need identified by GPS guided Grid or Zone Sampling.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Fertilizer that would have been spread in areas that do not need it can be placed in areas in need, thereby optimizing its use.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Around the world, precision agriculture developed at a varying pace.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precursor nations were the United States, Canada and Australia.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] In Europe, the United Kingdom was the first to go down this path, followed closely by France, where it first appeared in 1997–1998.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] In Latin America the leading country is Argentina, where it was introduced in the middle 1990s with the support of the National Agricultural Technology Institute.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Brazil established a state-owned enterprise, Embrapa, to research and develop sustainable agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The development of GPS and variable-rate spreading techniques helped to anchor precision farming management practices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Today, less than 10% of France's farmers are equipped with variable-rate systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Uptake of GPS is more widespread, but this hasn't stopped them using precision agriculture services, which supplies field-level recommendation maps.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] While digital technologies can transform the landscape of agricultural machinery, making mechanization both more precise and more accessible, non-mechanized production is still dominant in many low- and middle-income countries, especially in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Research on precision agriculture for non-mechanized production is increasing and so is its adoption.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Examples include the AgroCares hand-held soil scanner, uncrewed aerial vehicle (UAV) services (also known as drones), and GNSS to map field boundaries and establish land tenure.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] However, it is not clear how many agricultural producers actually use digital technologies.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision livestock farming supports farmers in real-time by continuously monitoring and controlling animal productivity, environmental impacts, and health and welfare parameters.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Sensors attached to animals or to barn equipment operate climate control and monitor animals’ health status, movement and needs.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] For example, cows can be tagged with the electronic identification (EID) that allows a milking robot to access a database of udder coordinates for specific cows.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Therefore, China is trying to better introduce precision agriculture technology into its own country and reduce some risks, paving the way for China's technology to develop precision agriculture in the future.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] In December 2014, the Russian President made an address to the Russian Parliament where he called for a National Technology Initiative.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] It is divided into subcomponents such as the FoodNet initiative.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The FoodNet initiative contains a set of declared priorities, such as precision agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This field is of special interest to Russia as an important tool in developing elements of the bioeconomy in Russia.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture, as the name implies, means the application of precise and correct amounts of inputs like water, fertilizer, pesticides, etc. at the correct time to the crop to increase its productivity and maximize its yields.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture management practices can significantly reduce the amount of nutrient and other crop inputs used while boosting yields.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Farmers thus obtain a return on their investment by saving on water, pesticide, and fertilizer costs.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The second, larger-scale benefit of targeting inputs concerns environmental impacts.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Applying the right amount of chemicals in the right place and at the right time benefits crops, soils and groundwater, and thus the entire crop cycle.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Consequently, precision agriculture has become a cornerstone of sustainable agriculture, since it respects crops, soils and farmers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Sustainable agriculture seeks to assure a continued supply of food within the ecological, economic and social limits required to sustain production in the long term.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] A 2013 article tried to show that precision agriculture can help farmers in developing countries like India.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture reduces the pressure of agriculture on the environment by increasing the efficiency of machinery and putting it into use.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] For example, the use of fleet digitalization techniques and GPS trackers reduces fuel consumption for agriculture, while variable rate application of nutrients or pesticides can potentially reduce the use of these inputs, thereby saving costs and reducing harmful runoff into the waterways.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] GPS also reduces the amount of compaction to the ground by following previously made guidance lines.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This will also allow for less time in the field and reduce the environmental impact of the equipment and chemicals.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture produces large quantities of varied sensing data which creates an opportunity to adapt and reuse such data for archaeology and heritage work, enhancing understanding of archaeology in contemporary agricultural landscapes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture is an application of breakthrough digital farming technologies.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Over $4.6 billion has been invested in agriculture tech companies—sometimes called agtech.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Driverless tractors have advanced significantly in the 2000s.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The tractor does most of the work, with the farmer stepping in for emergencies.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Technology is advancing towards driverless machinery programmed by GPS to spread fertilizer or plow land.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Autonomy of technology is driven by the demanding need for diagnoses, often difficult to accomplish solely by hands-on farmer-operated machinery.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] In many instances of high rates of production, manual adjustments cannot be sustained.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Other innovations include, partly solar powered, machines/robots that identify weeds and precisely kill them with a dose of a herbicide or lasers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Agricultural robots have been used for applications including weed control, herbicide application, picking, harvesting, seeding, and planting.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Advanced harvesting robots are being developed to identify ripe fruits, adjust to their shape and size, and carefully pluck them from branches.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Drone and satellite technology are used in precision farming.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This often occurs when drones take high-quality images while satellites capture the bigger picture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Aerial photography from light aircraft can be combined with data from satellite records to predict future yields based on the current level of field biomass.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Aggregated images can create contour maps to track where water flows, determine variable-rate seeding, and create yield maps of areas that were more or less productive.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The Internet of things is the network of physical objects outfitted with electronics that enable data collection and aggregation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] IoT comes into play with the development of sensors and farm-management software.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] For example, farmers can spectroscopically measure nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium in liquid manure, which is notoriously inconsistent.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] They can then scan the ground to see where cows have already urinated and apply fertilizer to only the spots that need it.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Moisture sensors in the soil determine the best times to remotely water plants.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The irrigation systems can be programmed to switch which side of the tree trunk they water based on the plant's need and rainfall.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Innovations are not just limited to plants—they can be used for the welfare of animals.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Cattle can be outfitted with internal sensors to keep track of stomach acidity and digestive problems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] External sensors track movement patterns to determine the cow's health and fitness, sense physical injuries, and identify the optimal times for breeding.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] All this data from sensors can be aggregated and analyzed to detect trends and patterns.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] As another example, monitoring technology can be used to make beekeeping more efficient.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Honeybees are of significant economic value and provide a vital service to agriculture by pollinating a variety of crops.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Monitoring of a honeybee colony's health via wireless temperature, humidity, and CO2 sensors helps to improve the productivity of bees, and to read early warnings in the data that might threaten the very survival of an entire hive.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Smartphone and tablet applications are becoming increasingly popular in precision agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Smartphones come with many useful applications already installed, including the camera, microphone, GPS, and accelerometer.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] There are also applications made dedicated to various agriculture applications such as field mapping, tracking animals, obtaining weather and crop information, and more.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] They are easily portable, affordable, and have high computing power.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Machine learning is commonly used in conjunction with drones, robots, and internet of things devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] It allows for the input of data from each of these sources.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The computer then processes this information and sends the appropriate actions back to these devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This allows for robots to deliver the perfect amount of fertilizer or for IoT devices to provide the perfect quantity of water directly to the soil.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Machine learning may also provide predictions to farmers at the point of need, such as the contents of plant-available nitrogen in soil, to guide fertilization planning.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] As more agriculture becomes ever more digital, machine learning will underpin efficient and precise farming with less manual labour.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Recent advancements in Generative AI and Large Language Models (LLM) have shifted precision agriculture from passive data analysis to active decision support.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] In 2025, the integration of AI agents has allowed farmers to interact with complex agronomic data using natural language, enabling real time queries about crop health or soil conditions.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Therefore, the use of Digital Twins (Virtual copies of physical fields) allow for the simulation of various environmental scenarios and management practices before they are applied in reality.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] This process significantly reduces operational risks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] The agricultural industry, including teachers, is still in the relatively early stages of precision agriculture technologies.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture has led many to believe that industry-related technologies should lead research and education instead of the other way around.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] In classrooms, conferences, workshops, and field days, educators of precision agriculture have struggled to keep up with the number of questions being asked.
[src:smart-farming-iot/precision-agriculture] Training people to use precision agriculture technologies has proven difficult, in contrast to teaching the fundamental ideas and concepts, which have been intuitive and rather straightforward.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] These are similar to wireless ad hoc networks in the sense that they rely on wireless connectivity and spontaneous formation of networks so that sensor data can be transported wirelessly.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs monitor physical conditions, such as temperature, sound, and pressure.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Modern networks are bi-directional, both collecting data and enabling control of sensor activity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The development of these networks was motivated by military applications such as battlefield surveillance.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Such networks are used in industrial and consumer applications, such as industrial process monitoring and control and machine health monitoring and agriculture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] A WSN is built of "nodes" – from a few to hundreds or thousands, where each node is connected to other sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Each such node typically has several parts: a radio transceiver with an internal antenna or connection to an external antenna, a microcontroller, an electronic circuit for interfacing with the sensors and an energy source, usually a battery or an embedded form of energy harvesting.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] A sensor node might vary in size from a shoebox to (theoretically) a grain of dust, although microscopic dimensions have yet to be realized.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor node cost is similarly variable, ranging from a few to hundreds of dollars, depending on node sophistication.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Size and cost constraints constrain resources such as energy, memory, computational speed and communications bandwidth.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The topology of a WSN can vary from a simple star network to an advanced multi-hop wireless mesh network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Propagation can employ routing or flooding.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] As of 2010, wireless sensor networks had deployed approximately 120 million remote units worldwide.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Area monitoring is a common application of WSNs.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] In area monitoring, the WSN is deployed over a region where some phenomenon is to be monitored.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] A military example is the use of sensors to detect enemy intrusion; a civilian example is the geo-fencing of gas or oil pipelines.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] There are several types of sensor networks for medical applications: implanted, wearable, and environment-embedded.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Implantable medical devices are those that are inserted inside the human body.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wearable devices are used on the body surface of a human or just at close proximity of the user.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Environment-embedded systems employ sensors contained in the environment.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Possible applications include body position measurement, location of persons, overall monitoring of ill patients in hospitals and at home.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Devices embedded in the environment track the physical state of a person for continuous health diagnosis, using as input the data from a network of depth cameras, a sensing floor, or other similar devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Body-area networks can collect information about an individual's health, fitness, and energy expenditure.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] In health care applications the privacy and authenticity of user data has prime importance.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Especially due to the integration of sensor networks, with IoT, the user authentication becomes more challenging; however, a solution is presented in recent work.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been used to monitor various species and habitats, beginning with the Great Duck Island Deployment, including marmots, cane toads in Australia and zebras in Kenya.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] There are many applications in monitoring environmental parameters, examples of which are given below.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] They share the extra challenges of harsh environments and reduced power supply.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Experiments have shown that personal exposure to air pollution in cities can vary a lot.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, it is of interest to have higher temporal and spatial resolution of pollutants and particulates.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] For research purposes, wireless sensor networks have been deployed to monitor the concentration of dangerous gases for citizens (e.g., in London).
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] However, sensors for gases and particulate matter suffer from high unit-to-unit variability, cross-sensitivities, and (concept) drift.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Moreover, the quality of data is currently insufficient for trustworthy decision-making, as field calibration leads to unreliable measurement results, and frequent recalibration might be required.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] A possible solution could be blind calibration or the usage of mobile references.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] A network of Sensor Nodes can be installed in a forest to detect when a fire has started.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The nodes can be equipped with sensors to measure temperature, humidity and gases which are produced by fire in the trees or vegetation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The early detection is crucial for a successful action of the firefighters; thanks to Wireless Sensor Networks, the fire brigade will be able to know when a fire is started and how it is spreading.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] A landslide detection system makes use of a wireless sensor network to detect the slight movements of soil and changes in various parameters that may occur before or during a landslide.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Through the data gathered it may be possible to know the impending occurrence of landslides long before it actually happens.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Water quality monitoring involves analyzing water properties in dams, rivers, lakes and oceans, as well as underground water reserves.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The use of many wireless distributed sensors enables the creation of a more accurate map of the water status, and allows the permanent deployment of monitoring stations in locations of difficult access, without the need of manual data retrieval.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks can be effective in preventing adverse consequences of natural disasters, like floods.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless nodes have been deployed successfully in rivers, where changes in water levels must be monitored in real time.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been developed for machinery condition-based maintenance (CBM) as they offer significant cost savings and enable new functionality.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensors can be placed in locations difficult or impossible to reach with a wired system, such as rotating machinery and untethered vehicles.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks also are used for the collection of data for monitoring of environmental information.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This can be as simple as monitoring the temperature in a fridge or the level of water in overflow tanks in nuclear power plants.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The statistical information can then be used to show how systems have been working.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The advantage of WSNs over conventional loggers is the "live" data feed that is possible.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Monitoring the quality and level of water includes many activities such as checking the quality of underground or surface water and ensuring a country's water infrastructure for the benefit of both human and animal.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] It may be used to protect the wastage of water.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] WSN can be used to monitor the condition of civil infrastructure and related geo-physical processes close to real time, and over long periods through data logging, using appropriately interfaced sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are used to monitor wine production, both in the field and the cellar.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The Wide Area Tracking System (WATS) is a prototype network for detecting a ground-based nuclear device such as a nuclear "briefcase bomb".
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] WATS is being developed at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL).
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would be made up of wireless gamma and neutron sensors connected through a communications network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Data picked up by the sensors undergoes "data fusion", which converts the information into easily interpreted forms; this data fusion is the most important aspect of the system.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The data fusion process occurs *within* the sensor network rather than at a centralized computer and is performed by a specially developed algorithm based on Bayesian statistics.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would not use a centralized computer for analysis because researchers found that factors such as latency and available bandwidth tended to create significant bottlenecks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Data processed in the field by the network itself (by transferring small amounts of data between neighboring sensors) is faster and makes the network more scalable.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] An important factor in WATS development is *ease of deployment*, since more sensors both improves the detection rate and reduces false alarms.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] WATS sensors could be deployed in permanent positions or mounted in vehicles for mobile protection of specific locations.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] One barrier to the implementation of WATS is the size, weight, energy requirements and cost of currently available wireless sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The development of improved sensors is a major component of current research at the Nonproliferation, Arms Control, and International Security (NAI) Directorate at LLNL.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] House of Representatives' Military Research and Development Subcommittee on October 1, 1997, during a hearing on nuclear terrorism and countermeasures.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] On August 4, 1998, in a subsequent meeting of that subcommittee, Chairman Curt Weldon stated that research funding for WATS had been cut by the Clinton administration to a subsistence level and that the program had been poorly re-organized.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Studies show that using sensors for incident monitoring improve the response of firefighters and police to an unexpected situation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] For an early detection of incidents we can use acoustic sensors to detect a spike in the noise of the city because of a possible accident, or use termic sensors to detect a possible fire.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Using low-power electronics, WSN:s can be cost-efficiently applied also in supply chains in various industries.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Cross-layer is becoming an important studying area for wireless communications.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The traditional layered approach does not have the ability to adapt to the environmental change.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Because of the interference between the different users, access conflicts, fading, and the change of environment in the wireless sensor networks, traditional layered approach for wired networks is not applicable to wireless networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] So the cross-layer can be used to make the optimal modulation to improve the transmission performance, such as data rate, energy efficiency, quality of service (QoS), etc.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor nodes can be imagined as small computers which are extremely basic in terms of their interfaces and their components.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] They usually consist of a *processing unit* with limited computational power and limited memory, *sensors* or MEMS (including specific conditioning circuitry), a *communication device* (usually radio transceivers or alternatively optical), and a power source usually in the form of a battery.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Other possible inclusions are energy harvesting modules, secondary ASICs, and possibly secondary communication interface (e.g.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The base stations are one or more components of the WSN with much more computational, energy and communication resources.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] They act as a gateway between sensor nodes and the end user as they typically forward data from the WSN on to a server.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Other special components in routing based networks are routers, designed to compute, calculate and distribute the routing tables.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] One major challenge in a WSN is to produce *low cost* and *tiny* sensor nodes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] There are an increasing number of small companies producing WSN hardware and the commercial situation can be compared to home computing in the 1970s.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Many of the nodes are still in the research and development stage, particularly their software.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Also inherent to sensor network adoption is the use of very low power methods for radio communication and data acquisition.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] In many applications, a WSN communicates with a local area network or wide area network through a gateway.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The Gateway acts as a bridge between the WSN and the other network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This enables data to be stored and processed by devices with more resources, for example, in a remotely located server.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] A wireless wide area network used primarily for low-power devices is known as a Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN).
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] There are several wireless standards and solutions for sensor node connectivity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Thread and Zigbee can connect sensors operating at 2.4 GHz with a data rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Many use a lower frequency to increase radio range (typically 1 km), for example Z-wave operates at 915 MHz (in North America) and in the EU 868 MHz has been widely used but these have a lower data rate (typically 50 kbit/s).
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The IEEE 802.15.4 working group provides a standard for low power device connectivity and commonly sensors and smart meters use one of these standards for connectivity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] With the emergence of Internet of Things, many other proposals have been made to provide sensor connectivity.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] LoRa is a form of LPWAN which provides long range low power wireless connectivity for devices, which has been used in smart meters and other long range sensor applications.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] NarrowBand IOT and LTE-M can connect up to millions of sensors and devices using cellular technology.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Energy is the scarcest resource of WSN nodes, and it determines the lifetime of WSNs.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs may be deployed in large numbers in various environments, including remote and hostile regions, where ad hoc communications are a key component.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Lifetime maximization: Energy/Power Consumption of the sensing device should be minimized and sensor nodes should be energy efficient since their limited energy resource determines their lifetime.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] To conserve power, wireless sensor nodes normally power off both the radio transmitter and the radio receiver when not in use.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are composed of low-energy, small-size, and low-range unattended sensor nodes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Recently, it has been observed that by periodically turning on and off the sensing and communication capabilities of sensor nodes, we can significantly reduce the active time and thus prolong network lifetime.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] However, this duty cycling may result in high network latency, routing overhead, and neighbor discovery delays due to asynchronous sleep and wake-up scheduling.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] These limitations call for a countermeasure for duty-cycled wireless sensor networks which should minimize routing information, routing traffic load, and energy consumption.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers from Sungkyunkwan University have proposed a lightweight non-increasing delivery-latency interval routing referred as LNDIR.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This scheme can discover minimum latency routes at each non-increasing delivery-latency interval instead of each time slot.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Simulation experiments demonstrated the validity of this novel approach in minimizing routing information stored at each sensor.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Furthermore, this novel routing can also guarantee the minimum delivery latency from each source to the sink.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Performance improvements of up to 12-fold and 11-fold are observed in terms of routing traffic load reduction and energy efficiency, respectively, as compared to existing schemes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Operating systems for wireless sensor network nodes are typically less complex than general-purpose operating systems.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] They more strongly resemble embedded systems, for two reasons.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] First, wireless sensor networks are typically deployed with a particular application in mind, rather than as a general platform.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Second, a need for low costs and low power leads most wireless sensor nodes to have low-power microcontrollers ensuring that mechanisms such as virtual memory are either unnecessary or too expensive to implement.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] It is therefore possible to use embedded operating systems such as eCos or uC/OS for sensor networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] However, such operating systems are often designed with real-time properties.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS, developed by David Culler, is perhaps the first operating system specifically designed for wireless sensor networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS is based on an event-driven programming model instead of multithreading.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS programs are composed of *event handlers* and *tasks* with run-to-completion semantics.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] When an external event occurs, such as an incoming data packet or a sensor reading, TinyOS signals the appropriate event handler to handle the event.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Event handlers can post tasks that are scheduled by the TinyOS kernel some time later.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] LiteOS is a newly developed OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides UNIX-like abstraction and support for the C programming language.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Contiki, developed by Adam Dunkels, is an OS which uses a simpler programming style in C while providing advances such as 6LoWPAN and Protothreads.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] RIOT (operating system) is a more recent real-time OS including similar functionality to Contiki.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] PreonVM is an OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides 6LoWPAN based on Contiki and support for the Java programming language.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Examples include Xively and the Wikisensing platform Archived 2021-06-09 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Such platforms simplify online collaboration between users over diverse data sets ranging from energy and environment data to that collected from transport services.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Other services include allowing developers to embed real-time graphs & widgets in websites; analyse and process historical data pulled from the data feeds; send real-time alerts from any datastream to control scripts, devices and environments.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] At present, agent-based modeling and simulation is the only paradigm which allows the simulation of complex behavior in the environments of wireless sensors (such as flocking).
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based simulation of wireless sensor and ad hoc networks is a relatively new paradigm.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based modelling was originally based on social simulation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Network simulators like Opnet, Tetcos NetSim and NS can be used to simulate a wireless sensor network.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Network localization refers to the problem of estimating the location of wireless sensor nodes during deployments and in dynamic settings.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] For ultra-low power sensors, size, cost and environment precludes the use of Global Positioning System receivers on sensors.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] In 2000, Nirupama Bulusu, John Heidemann and Deborah Estrin first motivated and proposed a radio connectivity based system for localization of wireless sensor networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Subsequently, such localization systems have been referred to as range free localization systems, and many localization systems for wireless sensor networks have been subsequently proposed including AHLoS, APS, and Stardust.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Sensors and devices used in wireless sensor networks are state-of-the-art technology with the lowest possible price.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The sensor measurements we get from these devices are therefore often noisy, incomplete and inaccurate.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers studying wireless sensor networks hypothesize that much more information can be extracted from hundreds of unreliable measurements spread across a field of interest than from a smaller number of high-quality, high-reliability instruments with the same total cost.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Macro-programming is a term coined by Matt Welsh.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] It refers to programming the entire sensor network as an ensemble, rather than individual sensor nodes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Another way to macro-program a network is to view the sensor network as a database, which was popularized by the TinyDB system developed by Sam Madden.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Reprogramming is the process of updating the code on the sensor nodes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The most feasible form of reprogramming is remote reprogramming whereby the code is disseminated wirelessly while the nodes are deployed.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Different reprogramming protocols exist that provide different levels of speed of operation, reliability, energy expenditure, requirement of code resident on the nodes, suitability to different wireless environments, resistance to DoS, etc.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Infrastructure-less architecture (i.e. no gateways are included, etc.) and inherent requirements (i.e. unattended working environment, etc.) of WSNs might pose several weak points that attract adversaries.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, security is a big concern when WSNs are deployed for special applications such as military and healthcare.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Owing to their unique characteristics, traditional security methods of computer networks would be useless (or less effective) for WSNs.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Hence, lack of security mechanisms would cause intrusions towards those networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] These intrusions need to be detected and mitigation methods should be applied.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] There have been important innovations in securing wireless sensor networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Most wireless embedded networks use omni-directional antennas and therefore neighbors can overhear communication in and out of nodes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This was used this to develop a primitive called "*local monitoring*" which was used for detection of sophisticated attacks, like blackhole or wormhole, which degrade the throughput of large networks to close-to-zero.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This primitive has since been used by many researchers and commercial wireless packet sniffers.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This was subsequently refined for more sophisticated attacks such as with collusion, mobility, and multi-antenna, multi-channel devices.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] If a centralized architecture is used in a sensor network and the central node fails, then the entire network will collapse, however the reliability of the sensor network can be increased by using a distributed control architecture.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] To provide nodes with backup in case of failure of the central node.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] There is also no centralised body to allocate the resources and they have to be self organized.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] The data gathered from wireless sensor networks is usually saved in the form of numerical data in a central base station.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] To reduce communication costs some algorithms remove or reduce nodes' redundant sensor information and avoid forwarding data that is of no use.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This technique has been used, for instance, for distributed anomaly detection or distributed optimization.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] As nodes can inspect the data they forward, they can measure averages or directionality for example of readings from other nodes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] For example, in sensing and monitoring applications, it is generally the case that neighboring sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation reduces the amount of network traffic which helps to reduce energy consumption on sensor nodes.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This is a form of in-network processing where sensor nodes are assumed to be unsecured with limited available energy, while the base station is assumed to be secure with unlimited available energy.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation complicates the already existing security challenges for wireless sensor networks and requires new security techniques tailored specifically for these scenarios.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Providing security to aggregate data in wireless sensor networks is known as *secure data aggregation in WSN*. were the first few works discussing techniques for secure data aggregation in wireless sensor networks.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Two main security challenges in secure data aggregation are confidentiality and integrity of data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] While encryption is traditionally used to provide end to end confidentiality in wireless sensor network, the aggregators in a secure data aggregation scenario need to decrypt the encrypted data to perform aggregation.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] This exposes the plaintext at the aggregators, making the data vulnerable to attacks from an adversary.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Similarly an aggregator can inject false data into the aggregate and make the base station accept false data.
[src:smart-farming-iot/wireless-sensor-network] Thus, while data aggregation improves energy efficiency of a network, it complicates the existing security challenges.
